title: Morning of Remembrance
moleskine:
Disclaimer - modify as necessary with or without weight vests
WARMUP:
Abe Vigoda - 9x in cadence
Side Straddle Hops - 11x in cadence
Michael Phelps - 9x in cadence

Imperial Walker - 11x in cadence

THE THANG:
9 Burpees on my down

Line up at goal line - run 100 yards
Everybody holds 1 low squat until everyone finishes
Back on goal line - run 100 yards to beginning
Hold 1 low squat until everyone finishes
9x Burpees on my down
Complete the above 10 times
Total of 2000 yards plus 1 low squat = 2001
9x Burpees 11 times
Never Forget. 

MARY:
Today marks 22 years since 9/11/2001
No Surrenders - 22x in cadence.
Never Forget.

Miles of Remembrance tonight - HC in #2nd-f channel - we will ruck together after all of the runners get started

THAT'S WHAT SHEETS SAID:  Today is a day to remember how our world changed so dramatically 22 years ago.  Let's remember the people that were lost, the families torn apart, the first responders going up the stairs in the towers while everyone else was trying to get out, and the veterans who selflessly give all across the world to keep us safe at home.  Let's spend the day thinking about them, finding ways to be kind to others, and being thankful for those who have served and continue to serve to protect us.  Never Forget.

COT:  Yes, please, and thank you.  Solemn remembrance.

Thank you for spending the morning in the gloom with me today.  I'm glad I was able to spend an important day with all of you.

title: Run and Gun
moleskine:
*WARMUP:*
SSH, Tin Soldier, Imperial walkers
*THE THANG:*
*Exercises completed until a pax decides it is time to run away from one station and run towards the new station. Various amounts of reps were performed until pax decided to move on

Station 1 - 
Kneeling curl to over head press
High Pull, shrugs
Curls - many variations
 --- Sprint 200 - 300 meters to next station 
Station 2 
Dead bugs
Heels to heaven
Posterior forearm holds
Flutter kicks

Station 3
Merkins, Derkins, Irkins, and more 
Hangs + Derkins
More Merkins

** The focus of the work out was that we were running away from one exercise (once we were nearing failure, but running towards something else). Between each station the following was read.

Often we:
Run away from conflict, when we should run towards understanding for the other person
Run away from fear, when we should run towards growth
Run away from addressing addiction, when we should run towards healing
Run away from bitterness, when we should run towards forgiveness
Run away from discipline, when we should run towards our values and commitment
Run away from hearing other peoples opinions or beliefs, when we should run towards being able to articulate our own beliefs 

*MARY:*
Done Throughout

*ANNOUNCEMENTS:*

Prayers for the men in the circle - may we not find ourselves alone on the field of battle when the fight comes to us

THAT'S WHAT SHEETS SAID:
While F3 is about Fitness, Fellowship, and Faith and may seem like it is all about ourselves, it really isn't.  It's about getting ourselves right and keeping ourselves healthy (body, heart, and mind) for those that are important to us (Ms, 2.0s, Family, F3 Brothers....).  Let's be mindful of this, and while doing some of the things to keep ourselves healthy may appear selfish on the surface, it is important that we take care or ourselves for the others in our lives.  Keep exercising, eating right, watching what you are putting in your body (food) and mind (relationships + faith).  Be connected with and be there for others - for them.  Thank you to all of you for your contributions to the conversation and being there this morning for me.

Today's mosey was a lot like life - there will be people leading the pack, several of us in the middle, and some bring up the rear. —————

This morning we exercised our physical grips, trained our bodies so as to be in line with our minds. The shared leadership and camaraderie in was awesome to witness. Thank you for being present for each other and pushing one another to be better. We ended with the following quote from Seneca, reminding us that it is in good times we prepare for the trials and struggles ahead, not at the time of the struggle itself.

“Here's a lesson to test your mind's mettle: take part of a week in which you have only the most meager and cheap food, dress scantly in shabby clothes, and ask yourself if this is really the worst that you feared. It is when times are good that you should gird yourself for tougher times ahead, for when Fortune is kind the soul can build defenses against her ravages. So it is that soldiers practice maneuvers in peacetime, erecting bunkers with no enemies in sight and exhausting themselves under no attack so that when it comes they won't grow tired." 

Ax3,
Wooderson

Fear is a healthy part of our psyche, but it can also be a major hindrance in our lives.  Fear keeps us safe - things like crossing the street without looking.  At the same time, it can paralyze us - causing us to over analyze and not move forward with our lives.  Let's all be aware of fear in our lives and overcome it so we can keep pushing ahead. “Nothing ever doesn’t change, but nothing changes much.” OK GO, White Knuckles

Coming out and putting in the reps is how we make incremental progress towards our ideals. Like the song says, “Nothing ever doesn’t change” or another words, “things are always changing.” If we’re not coming out and putting in the reps, change still happens, it’s just not in our control “what” changes. When we put in the effort, little by little, positive change will happen. And because we are putting in the effort, we decide in what direction our changes is happening. 
This is a principle of change for fitness: be it physical, emotional, spiritual, mental, work, education…it all requires incremental improvement.

THAT'S WHAT SHEETS SAID:
Each of you PAX did what needed done today - by showing up.  For me, sometimes that is the hardest part of life - showing up.  I've recently struggled in other aspects of my life by not wanting to show up - whether it be for family obligations, things that need done around the house, or things I should be doing with my kids.  The reminder for me is to take what I have in F3 - no matter how tired I am, if I just show up, actually doing what needs done automatically follows.  I have HIMs surrounding me, pushing me, supporting me when the going is tough, but I can keep going.  Well done in showing up this morning and pushing yourself and each other - my hope is that we can all carry this forward consistently in the other aspects of our lives.

COT: Yes, please and thank you.

Imagine showing up to not only welcome our newest relocated PAX, Blackbeard (welcome), but seeing that Twister 🌪️ was back in town. My heart is full this morning as I came back to the gloom of The Home of F3 Boise surrounded by the wisdom, grit, and love that these men bring to the table in support of one another.

30/30 discussion this morning surrounded the 5 Core Principles of F3 - what they mean to PAX, why they’re important, and how F3 has impacted their lives. It’s a beautiful thing to see men post in support of their own goals, and those of their fellow peers. The hardships and joys in life will come for us all. When they do, you won’t be facing either alone.

YHC,
Wooderson - Ax3

THAT'S WHAT SHEETS SAID:
Our daily habits are what will lead us to success and contentment in life.  Everything from what we put into our bodies, when we go to bed and get up in the morning, what we do in our free time and watch on TV, the language we choose to use, and especially the people we surround ourselves with.  I have chosen to start my days getting up for an early BD and surround myself with people that are good influences on my life (my F3 Brothers).  This is applicable for all of us, but especially the young men who joined - now is the time to rethink our habits and make those good choices automatic in our lives and get rid of the garbage.  Thank you all for being there for me this morning!

COT: Yes, please, and thank you.  @Strings with prayer to take us out.

SPECIAL THANKS:  It was a great day to have three young men with us.  @Huckleberry and @Yardstick - great work getting those 2.0s to join.  They all held their own.  I was proud to bring my 2.0 out to see something that is important in my life and show him the example set by all of you HIMs.

This past weekend, I had the opportunity to volunteer with my son at the Idaho Foodbank with a great group of PAX ant their families and had a great time. Doing things to focus on others instead of myself helps me in my pursuit of happiness, and is something important to teach my kids. moleskine:

50lb+ rucks with SB, header over to a table.
4 PAX at a table, the other 3 were carrying SB.

Started out with table having 4 SB on top, so other 3 SB were carried by the others not on the table.

Carried the table around bellagio. Alternating PAX on which 4 were carrying the table. Eventually removing the SB off the table, so the other PAX were carrying double SB or sometimes triple SBs.

Ended the loop with 2 PAX carrying the table, with rest of the PAX carrying the rest of the SB.

Next phase: Canuck with his ruck was laying on the table, and the other 6 carried the table across the field. We successfully gently put it down. haha. Then 5 PAX pushed the table back with Freighter on the way back. 

4 PAX carried Puff across the field, 3 PAX carried Freighter back.

Grab all gear and headed back to cars.

—————
Thanks for allowing me to try something new this AM, Gentlemen. While some improvements will be made and reiterated, I think the intention was fulfilled - carrying and sharing the load of life. 

Never forget that you are not in this alone. You may not always ask for it, nor do you need to. Sometimes, it falls on us to simply come along side and encourage/aid our fellow man. Even when the burden is ours to carry, we can learn to share parts and lean on others with more intention.

Be present. Be observant. Give love. Receive love. Practice sharing and shouldering.

YHC - Ax3
